      &quot;Whenever I go, I attend to God (<font face="Gulim, sans-serif">&#54616;&#45208;&#45784;</font>). Even God doesn&#8217;t like it, He can&#8217;t help but be with me. When you are asked &#8216;Where is God?&#8217;, there will be answers in thousands of directions, (but I will say,) &#8216;God represents me,&#8217; &#8216; which is &#8216;<font face="Gulim, sans-serif">&#54620;&#45208;&#45784;</font><font face="Arial Unicode MS">&#8217; </font>(Han Na Nim; Father&#8217;s coined word, which consists of &#8216;<font face="Gulim, sans-serif">&#54620;</font>/ Han: one,&#8217; &#8216;<font face="Gulim, sans-serif">&#45208;</font>/ Na: I or myself,&#8217; and <font face="Gulim, sans-serif">&#45784;</font>/ Nim, a honorific title.) Everything will become &#8216;<font face="Gulim, sans-serif">&#54620;&#45208;&#45784;</font>.&#8217; You&#8217;ve just heard such an explanation for the first time, haven't you? God has been ambiguous, but it is only the Korean people (<font face="Gulim, sans-serif">&#54620;&#48124;&#51313;</font>/ Han Min Jok:) that found God Which represents &#8216;I&#8217;.&#160;
    </p>
  </body>
</html>
</richcontent>
